declare(strict_types=1);
echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">Eastern religious traditions at thesis level — faith, doctrine, dogma, proselytism, apostasy, birth, marriage, death, metempsychosis, and karma for each tradition.</p>';

// HINDUISM
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#b7791f;">⊕ Hinduism — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Panentheistic — Brahman encompasses all; functionally polytheistic through the devas | <strong>Scripture:</strong> Vedas, Upanishads, Bhagavad Gita, Puranas</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Hindu faith (shraddha — literally "placing the heart on") is not primarily propositional but relational and experiential. One does not "believe in" Hinduism as one believes a mathematical theorem; one inhabits it through practice, ritual, family, and community. The absence of a founding prophet, a single binding creed, or a central authority means that Hindu "belief" encompasses an extraordinary range of positions — from the strict non-dualism of Advaita Vedanta (the world is illusion; only Brahman is real) to the devotional theism of Vaishnavism (God is a personal being who loves his devotees) to the ritual polytheism of popular practice (offering to Ganesha before an exam, to Lakshmi for prosperity, to Durga for protection).</p>';
echo '<p>What unifies these positions is not doctrine but practice and the acknowledgment of the Vedas as authoritative. A Hindu who rejects the existence of God can still be Hindu if they accept the Vedic tradition. A Hindu who worships one God exclusively can still honor all gods as aspects of that One. This philosophical flexibility is Hinduism\'s greatest strength and its greatest challenge to outside understanding.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Brahman</strong> — the ultimate reality, infinite, self-existent, beyond all attributes in its highest form (nirguna Brahman — Brahman without qualities). In saguna form (Brahman with qualities), it manifests as the personal God worshipped in devotion.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Atman</strong> — the individual soul; in Advaita, identical with Brahman ("Tat tvam asi" — That thou art); in Vishishtadvaita, a real individual within Brahman; in Dvaita, eternally distinct from God.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Maya</strong> — the cosmic illusion or creative power that makes the world appear as separate from Brahman. Not "the world is unreal" but "the world as separately existing from Brahman is the illusion."</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Dharma</strong> — cosmic and personal order; one\'s duty appropriate to one\'s nature (svadharma), stage of life (ashrama), and social position (varna). Dharma is context-specific and dynamic — there is no single ethical code for all persons in all situations.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Four Goals of Life (Purusharthas)</strong> — Dharma (righteousness/duty), Artha (wealth/prosperity), Kama (pleasure/desire), and Moksha (liberation). A complete human life pursues all four in proper balance, with Moksha as the ultimate aim.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Dogma</h3>';
echo '<p>Hinduism has no formal dogma in the Catholic sense — no council has defined binding articles of faith. However, the following positions function as near-universal orthodox positions:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The authority of the Vedas (those who reject Vedic authority are classified as nastika — heterodox)</li>';
echo '<li>The reality of karma and samsara</li>';
echo '<li>The possibility of moksha (liberation) as the highest human goal</li>';
echo '<li>The existence of Brahman as the ultimate reality</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Classical Hinduism does not proselytize — it is a tradition of birth and initiation, not conversion. The concepts of caste (jati) and lineage (kula) make Hinduism fundamentally a community-embedded tradition rather than a universal religion that anyone can join by declaring belief. One is born Hindu; one receives the sacred thread (upanayana) that marks full membership in the tradition.</p>';
echo '<p>However, this picture is complicated by:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>ISKCON (Hare Krishnas)</strong> — actively welcomes converts; treats all people as potential Vaishnavas; has initiated hundreds of thousands of Western devotees into Gaudiya Vaishnavism since the 1960s</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Arya Samaj</strong> — 19th-century reform movement that advocated shuddhi (purification/reconversion) of those who had converted away from Hinduism and welcomed new converts</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ramakrishna Mission</strong> — teaches universal religion; Swami Vivekananda declared at the 1893 Parliament of World Religions that Hinduism accepts all paths to God; welcomes spiritual seekers of all backgrounds</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ghar wapsi</strong> — modern Hindu nationalist "homecoming" ceremonies reconverting Christians and Muslims declared to be of Hindu ancestry</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Traditional Hinduism has no formal apostasy mechanism — one cannot exactly "leave" Hinduism since membership is by birth. A Hindu who converts to Christianity or Islam is described as having "gone out of the fold" (dharma-bhrashta — fallen from dharma). Traditional consequences include:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>Loss of caste status and exclusion from caste rituals</li>';
echo '<li>Exclusion from ancestral ceremonies (shraddha) — the converted person cannot perform the rites that feed the ancestors</li>';
echo '<li>Social ostracism in traditional communities</li>';
echo '<li>In contemporary India, conversion from Hinduism has become politically charged; several states have enacted "anti-conversion" laws requiring government notification before conversion</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<p>There is no Hindu equivalent of the Islamic death penalty for apostasy, though historically violence against converts has occurred in communally charged contexts.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions — The Sixteen Samskaras</h3>';
echo '<p>Hinduism has the most elaborate life-cycle ritual system of any world religion — the sixteen samskaras (sacraments/rites of passage) marking every significant transition from conception to death:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Garbhadhana</strong> — rite of conception; prayers for the creation of new life</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Pumsavana</strong> — performed in the third month of pregnancy; prayers for a healthy child</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Simantonnayana</strong> — performed in the sixth or eighth month; hair-parting ceremony for the mother</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Jatakarma</strong> — performed immediately at birth; the father touches the baby\'s lips with honey and ghee, whispers the child\'s secret name, and prays for intelligence and long life</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Namakarana</strong> — naming ceremony on the 11th or 12th day; the child receives its public name, chosen according to astrological calculation and family tradition</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Nishkramana</strong> — first outing; the child is taken outside and shown the sun for the first time</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Annaprashana</strong> — first solid food (rice); typically in the sixth month; a moment of celebration and feeding by elders</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Chudakarana</strong> — first haircut (tonsure); typically in the first or third year; the child\'s birth hair is shaved, symbolizing the removal of past-life karma</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Karnavedha</strong> — ear-piercing ceremony</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Vidyarambha</strong> — beginning of education; the child traces letters in rice or sand</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Upanayana</strong> — sacred thread ceremony; the most important male samskara; initiates the boy into the student stage of life (brahmacharya); he receives the sacred thread (yajnopavita) and is taught the Gayatri Mantra; traditionally for upper-caste males at ages 8, 11, or 12</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Vedarambha</strong> — formal commencement of Vedic study</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Keshanta</strong> — first shaving of the beard</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Samavartana</strong> — graduation from studentship</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Vivaha</strong> — marriage (see below)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Antyesti</strong> — funeral rites (see below)</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage — Vivaha</h3>';
echo '<p>Hindu marriage is a samskara — a sacrament that transforms both parties and creates a new spiritual unit. The marriage ceremony (vivaha) involves fire as the sacred witness (Agni) and is built around the Saptapadi — seven steps taken together around the sacred fire, each step accompanied by a specific vow:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>Step 1 — for food and nourishment</li>';
echo '<li>Step 2 — for strength and vitality</li>';
echo '<li>Step 3 — for prosperity</li>';
echo '<li>Step 4 — for happiness</li>';
echo '<li>Step 5 — for progeny</li>';
echo '<li>Step 6 — for long life</li>';
echo '<li>Step 7 — for friendship and companionship</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<p>After the seventh step, the marriage is irrevocable under traditional law. The bride and groom exchange garlands (varmala) and the groom ties the mangalsutra (sacred thread/necklace) around the bride\'s neck — the Hindu equivalent of a wedding ring. The sindoor (vermilion) is applied to the parting of the bride\'s hair by the groom.</p>';
echo '<p><strong>Caste endogamy</strong> remains the norm in most Hindu communities — marriage within one\'s caste (jati) and sub-caste (upajati) but outside one\'s gotra (patrilineal clan). Intercaste marriage, legal since 1955, remains controversial in many communities and is a source of significant social tension.</p>';
echo '<p><strong>Dowry (Dahej)</strong> — gifts from the bride\'s family — is legally prohibited (Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961) but culturally persistent. Dowry harassment and violence (including "dowry deaths") remain serious problems in India.</p>';

echo '<h3>Death and Burial — Antyesti</h3>';
echo '<p>The Hindu funeral (antyesti — "last sacrifice") is governed by the principle that death is a transition requiring ritual assistance. The dying person should be placed on the ground (return to earth), given water from the Ganges, and have the Gayatri Mantra whispered in their ear. The moment of death, ideally, finds the person in a state of meditation and conscious surrender.</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Preparation</strong> — the body is washed, anointed with ghee and sandalwood paste, wrapped in white cloth, and decorated with flowers</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Cremation (dahana)</strong> — the body is cremated on a pyre, traditionally lit by the eldest son (or nearest male relative); cremation returns the body to the five elements (panchamahabhutas); the skull is cracked open at the appropriate moment to release the soul</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Timing</strong> — cremation should occur within 24 hours of death; ideally before the next sunrise</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ashes (asthi)</strong> — collected on the third day and immersed in a sacred river; the Ganges at Varanasi (Kashi) is the most auspicious; dying in Kashi is believed to guarantee liberation regardless of one\'s karma</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Shraddha</strong> — ancestral rites performed on specific lunar dates (particularly during Pitru Paksha — the fortnight of ancestors); the deceased is offered pinda (rice balls) and water to nourish them in the ancestral realm; failure to perform shraddha is believed to cause the ancestors to become dissatisfied and bring misfortune</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Mourning</strong> — typically 13 days of ritual impurity for the immediate family; specific rites on the 13th day (terahi) formally conclude the acute mourning period</li>';
echo '<li><strong>One-year anniversary</strong> — the annual shraddha (shraddha tithi) is observed on the anniversary of death for as long as the children live</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Metempsychosis and Karma — Full Treatment</h3>';
echo '<p>See the dedicated <a href="/subjects/religion/metempsychosis/">Metempsychosis and Karma</a> page for the full comparative treatment. The Hindu doctrine is summarized here:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Samsara</strong> — the cycle of birth, death, and rebirth through all forms of life driven by karma and desire</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Karma</strong> — three types: Sanchita (total accumulated), Prarabdha (currently being experienced), Kriyamana (being created now)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender in reincarnation</strong> — cross-gender incarnation fully accepted; gender is a function of karma, not of soul essence</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Cross-species</strong> — fully accepted; the soul cycles through 8.4 million species before achieving human birth</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Moksha</strong> — liberation from samsara; the cessation of karma and the recognition of Atman\'s identity with Brahman</li>';
echo '</ul>';

// BUDDHISM
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2d6a1f;">⊕ Buddhism — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Non-theistic (no creator God); later traditions develop devotional relationships with Buddhas and Bodhisattvas | <strong>Scripture:</strong> Pali Canon (Theravada), Mahayana Sutras, Tibetan Canon</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Buddhism\'s relationship to faith is philosophically distinctive. The Buddha explicitly discouraged blind acceptance of teachings on the basis of authority, tradition, or reasoning alone (Kalama Sutta). Faith (saddha in Pali; shraddha in Sanskrit) in Buddhism is not the starting point but a consequence — confidence that develops through practice and experience. One begins with provisional trust in the Three Jewels (Buddha, Dharma, Sangha), tests the teaching through meditation and ethical practice, and develops faith as the practice bears fruit.</p>';
echo '<p>The question "Does God exist?" is famously declared by the Buddha to be one of the "unanswered questions" (avyakata) — not because the answer is unknown but because engaging the question does not lead to liberation. Buddhism is not atheistic in the sense of asserting God\'s non-existence; it is pragmatically agnostic about metaphysical questions that do not bear on the cessation of suffering.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>The Three Marks of Existence (Tilakkhana)</strong> — Anicca (impermanence: all conditioned phenomena arise and pass away), Dukkha (suffering/unsatisfactoriness: clinging to impermanent things causes suffering), Anatta (no-self: there is no permanent, unchanging self in any phenomenon)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Dependent Origination (Paticca-samuppada)</strong> — all phenomena arise in dependence on conditions; nothing exists independently; the twelve links of dependent origination describe the chain of causation that perpetuates samsara from ignorance through death and rebirth</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Two Truths</strong> (Mahayana) — Conventional truth (the world as it appears, where persons and objects exist and function) and Ultimate truth (sunyata — emptiness; at the deepest level, all phenomena lack inherent existence). Nagarjuna\'s Madhyamaka philosophy argues that these two truths are not contradictory but complementary perspectives on the same reality.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Buddha-nature (Tathagatagarbha)</strong> — Mahayana doctrine that all sentient beings possess the seed or essence of Buddhahood within them; liberation is the actualization of this already-present nature, not the acquisition of something new</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Dogma</h3>';
echo '<p>Buddhism is notably undogmatic compared to the Abrahamic religions. The Buddha\'s teaching style was consistently pragmatic: "I teach suffering and the cessation of suffering." The Theravada tradition has the most rigid canon — the Pali Canon is the definitive word of the Buddha; later additions are rejected. Mahayana Buddhism accepts additional sutras as authentic Buddha-word even though they were composed centuries after the historical Buddha\'s death — a position Theravada rejects as spurious. Despite these differences, no Buddhist council has issued binding anathemas or declared heretics in the way Christian councils have.</p>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Buddhism has a strong missionary tradition — the Buddha specifically sent his first disciples out to teach "for the welfare of the many, out of compassion for the world." But Buddhist proselytism has been characterized by persuasion and example rather than coercion. Emperor Ashoka (3rd century BCE) spread Buddhism across Asia through missions, infrastructure, and example — not conquest. Buddhist missionaries adapted their teaching to local cultures (a process called "skillful means" — upaya), which produced the extraordinary diversity of Buddhist traditions across Asia.</p>';
echo '<p>Modern Buddhism actively welcomes converts through dharma centers, meditation classes, books, and online teaching. The barrier to becoming Buddhist is low — taking refuge in the Three Jewels is all that is formally required. Many Westerners practice Buddhism without formally converting, or combine Buddhist meditation with their existing religious identity.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Buddhism has no concept of apostasy equivalent to Islam or medieval Christianity. One can leave Buddhism — simply by ceasing to take refuge in the Three Jewels — without any formal consequence. There is no Buddhist equivalent of excommunication, and no tradition of punishing those who leave. The teaching is that each person must walk the path for themselves; coercing religious identity is antithetical to the first precept (non-harming) and to the Buddha\'s own teaching style. A monk who leaves the monastic order (disrobes) may do so simply by declaring it before witnesses; they return to lay life without stigma in most traditions.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<p>Buddhist birth traditions vary enormously by culture and tradition:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Theravada</strong> — monks may chant Paritta (protective suttas) for the pregnant mother and the newborn; the infant is brought to the temple to receive blessings; naming may involve the monk choosing an auspicious name from the Buddhist calendar</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Tibetan Buddhism</strong> — a lama may be consulted to determine the child\'s astrological circumstances and spiritual connections; if the child shows signs of being a tulku (reincarnate lama), specific tests are conducted; the child may receive blessings from a senior lama</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Japanese Buddhism (Jodo Shinshu, Zen, etc.)</strong> — the infant is presented at the temple; receives a Buddhist name (homyo) in some traditions; the Hanamatsuri (Buddha\'s birthday festival, April 8) is a major occasion involving children</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Sri Lankan</strong> — thread ceremony (pirith nool): monks tie a blessed thread around the infant\'s wrist for protection</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage Traditions</h3>';
echo '<p>Buddhism has no sacrament of marriage — marriage is understood as a civil and social institution, not a religious one in the strict sense. The Buddha said relatively little about marriage. Monks may be invited to bless a marriage, chant protective suttas, and offer teachings on the responsibilities of spouses to each other. In Theravada countries (Sri Lanka, Thailand, Myanmar), monks do not perform marriages themselves; the civil ceremony is separate from the Buddhist blessing. In Japan, Shinto ceremonies are traditionally used for weddings even by Buddhist families. In Tibet, marriage ceremonies are performed by lay specialists, not monks.</p>';
echo '<p>Buddhist ethics regarding marriage emphasize: sexual fidelity (part of the third precept — no sexual misconduct), mutual respect and care, and the home as a place of spiritual cultivation as well as material life. The Buddha praised the householder\'s path as fully capable of leading to liberation, not as a lesser option than monasticism.</p>';

echo '<h3>Death and Burial</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Theravada</strong> — monks chant suttas for the dying and the dead; the Metta Sutta (loving-kindness) and Paritta are especially used; the dying are encouraged to maintain mindfulness, recall meritorious deeds, and contemplate the Buddha; cremation is the norm (following the Buddha\'s own cremation)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Tibetan Buddhism — Sky Burial (jhator)</strong> — the body is offered to vultures on a high rock platform, returning the body to nature while the consciousness has already departed; the Bardo Thodol (Tibetan Book of the Dead) is read aloud for 49 days to guide the consciousness through the intermediate state (bardo) between death and rebirth; the Rigpa (awareness) is introduced to the Clear Light of reality at the moment of death</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Japanese Buddhism</strong> — the funeral is almost universally Buddhist in Japan (even for those who marry Shinto); the deceased receives a posthumous Buddhist name (kaimyo) for a fee paid to the temple; elaborate memorial services at 7 days, 49 days, 1 year, 3 years, 7 years, and 13 years; the Obon festival (mid-August) is the annual reunion of the living with ancestral spirits</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Chinese and Vietnamese Buddhism</strong> — monks chant sutras for 49 days (the duration of the bardo in Mahayana teaching); burning of paper goods (money, houses, cars) to provide for the deceased in the afterlife</li>';
echo '</ul>';

// SIKHISM
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2b6cb0;">⊕ Sikhism — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Strictly monotheistic — Ik Onkar (One God) | <strong>Scripture:</strong> Guru Granth Sahib (eternal, living Guru)</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Sikh faith (vishvas) is rooted in direct experience of God\'s presence through naam simran (meditation on God\'s name) rather than in doctrinal assent to propositions. Guru Nanak\'s founding declaration — "There is no Hindu, there is no Muslim" — was not a rejection of religion but an insistence that the direct experience of the divine transcends religious labels. Sikh theology insists that God can be experienced directly by anyone who sincerely meditates on the divine name (Waheguru, Sat Naam — True Name).</p>';
echo '<p>The central act of Sikh faith is not believing but listening — Gurbani (the divine word in the Guru Granth Sahib) is received through deep, attentive listening (shravana) that gradually transforms the hearer. The Guru Granth Sahib is not merely a book of doctrine but a living presence — it is installed on a throne, fanned, put to rest each night, and awakened each morning, because it is the eternal Guru, not a historical document.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Ik Onkar</strong> — "There is One God." The Mool Mantar (root mantra) opening the Guru Granth Sahib: "Ik Onkar, Sat Naam, Karta Purakh, Nirbhau, Nirvair, Akal Murat, Ajuni, Saibhang, Gurprasad" — One God, True Name, Creator, Without Fear, Without Enmity, Timeless Form, Unborn, Self-Existent, Known by Guru\'s Grace.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Haumai (Ego)</strong> — the fundamental human problem; the false sense of separate self that creates the five thieves: Kaam (lust), Krodh (anger), Lobh (greed), Moh (attachment), and Ahankar (pride/ego). These five vices are the obstacles to experiencing God.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Seva (Selfless Service)</strong> — service to others as a form of worship; the Sikh who serves the community without expectation of reward worships God in the world. Langar (free community kitchen) is seva in institutional form.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Sangat (Holy Company)</strong> — the community of believers; the spiritual environment that supports the individual\'s practice. "In the company of saints, the mind turns toward God."</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Waheguru</strong> — the primary Sikh name for God; literally "Wonderful Guru/Lord"; an expression of wonder at the divine that is simultaneously a name and an exclamation of praise.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Dogma</h3>';
echo '<p>Sikhism\'s non-negotiable positions:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>Ik Onkar — God is absolutely One; any form of idol worship (murti puja) is rejected</li>';
echo '<li>The Guru Granth Sahib is the eternal, living Guru; no human being can claim to be a Guru after Guru Gobind Singh</li>';
echo '<li>The Ten Gurus\' authority and succession are accepted</li>';
echo '<li>The Khalsa (community of the pure) and the Five Ks are obligatory for initiated Sikhs</li>';
echo '<li>Caste discrimination is rejected: all humans are equal before God regardless of caste, gender, or religion</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Sikhism does not actively proselytize — it does not send missionaries to convert others. However, it welcomes anyone who sincerely wishes to follow the Guru\'s path. The gurdwara (Sikh place of worship) is open to all regardless of faith, caste, or background. The langar (free community kitchen) feeds anyone who comes, with no requirement to be Sikh. Initiation into the Khalsa (Amrit Sanchar) is available to anyone — of any background — who sincerely commits to the Sikh way of life. In practice, most Sikhs are born into Sikh families, but conversion is accepted and welcomed.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>A Sikh who abandons the faith — particularly one who was initiated into the Khalsa and then removes the Five Ks — is described as a patit (fallen one). This carries significant social consequences in traditional Sikh communities: exclusion from Khalsa ceremonies, social disapproval, and the perception of having broken a sacred vow made before the Guru. However, there is no death penalty and no formal legal consequence. The Sikh Rehat Maryada (code of conduct) prescribes specific penalties (tanakha) for violations of the Khalsa code, to be determined by the community, but these are rehabilitative rather than punitive in nature. A patit who sincerely repents and takes Amrit again is fully readmitted.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Naam Karan (Naming Ceremony)</strong> — performed at the gurdwara when the mother has recovered from childbirth; the Guru Granth Sahib is opened at random and the first letter of the first word on the left page becomes the first letter of the child\'s name; this random opening (hukamnama — God\'s command) is believed to be divinely guided</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ardas (Prayer)</strong> — prayers of thanksgiving for the birth are offered in the gurdwara</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Amrit (Sweetened water)</strong> — the granthi (reader) dips a kirpan (ceremonial sword) in water sweetened with sugar (amrit) and places a drop on the baby\'s tongue; the remainder is given to the mother</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender equality</strong> — Sikhism explicitly rejects differential treatment of male and female children; female infanticide (historically practiced in some Punjabi communities) is condemned</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage — Anand Karaj</h3>';
echo '<p>The Sikh wedding ceremony (Anand Karaj — "Blissful Union") is performed in the presence of the Guru Granth Sahib. The couple circles the Guru Granth Sahib four times (laavan) while the corresponding wedding hymn (composed by Guru Ram Das) is sung:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>First lavan</strong> — duty to family and community; the beginning of the spiritual journey</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Second lavan</strong> — the meeting of the couple\'s souls with each other and with God</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Third lavan</strong> — detachment from the world and longing for God</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Fourth lavan</strong> — union with God; bliss; the couple has become one</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<p>The Anand Karaj is conducted before the congregation (sangat) and requires no priest beyond the granthi who reads the scripture. Both parties must be Sikh for an Anand Karaj (a ruling reinforced by the Akal Takht in 2012, which caused controversy in diaspora communities where interfaith marriages are more common).</p>';
echo '<p><strong>Dowry</strong> — explicitly rejected by Sikh teaching; the Gurus condemned the dowry system. In practice, it persists in some Punjabi Sikh families.</p>';

echo '<h3>Death and Burial</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Antam Sanskar (Last Rites)</strong> — the body is washed and dressed (in the Five Ks for an initiated Sikh); the Nitnem (daily prayers) are recited</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Cremation</strong> — the norm; the body is cremated, ideally on a pyre though in Western countries a crematorium is used; the eldest son (or nearest relative) lights the pyre</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ashes</strong> — immersed in flowing water; for many diaspora Sikhs this means a special trip to a river in Punjab (the Sutlej, Beas, or Ravi)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Sahaj Path or Akhand Path</strong> — the complete Guru Granth Sahib may be read (Akhand Path — continuous 48-hour reading; or Sahaj Path — broken reading over several days) in memory of the deceased</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Antam Ardas</strong> — final prayer committing the soul to God</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Mourning</strong> — grief is permitted but excessive lamentation is discouraged; death is understood as the soul\'s return to God ("Waheguru di amaanat wapis ho gayi" — God\'s trust has been returned)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Afterlife</strong> — the soul returns to Waheguru; detailed descriptions of heaven and hell are avoided; the emphasis is on union with God (mukti/moksha) vs continued separation from God through the cycle of rebirths</li>';
echo '</ul>';

// ZOROASTRIANISM
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#553c9a;">⊕ Zoroastrianism — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Monotheistic (Ahura Mazda) with cosmic dualism (the opposition of Angra Mainyu) | <strong>Scripture:</strong> The Avesta (Gathas of Zarathustra)</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Zoroastrian faith (daena — literally "religion/vision") is centered on an active, moral engagement with the cosmic struggle between good (asha — truth/righteousness) and evil (druj — the lie/falsehood). Zoroastrianism is one of the most ethically demanding of all religions — faith without righteous action is meaningless. The Three Pillars — Humata (Good Thoughts), Hukhta (Good Words), Hvarshta (Good Deeds) — encapsulate the entire ethical system. Belief in Ahura Mazda is meaningless without living by these principles in every aspect of daily life.</p>';
echo '<p>Zoroastrian cosmology is explicitly dualistic at the phenomenal level: Ahura Mazda (the Wise Lord — all good, all light, all truth) and Angra Mainyu / Ahriman (the Destructive Spirit — all evil, all darkness, all lies) are in cosmic combat. Humans must choose their side — and this choice is made in every thought, word, and action. There is no neutral position. The universe is a battleground and every human life is a campaign in that battle.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Ahura Mazda</strong> — the supreme deity; creator of all that is good, true, and light; the object of Zoroastrian worship and devotion; known through the Amesha Spentas (Holy Immortals) — six divine attributes/beings that emanate from Ahura Mazda and embody specific aspects of goodness (Vohu Manah — Good Mind, Asha Vahishta — Best Truth, Khshathra Vairya — Desirable Dominion, Spenta Armaiti — Holy Devotion, Haurvatat — Wholeness, Ameretat — Immortality)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Free Will</strong> — Zoroastrianism places extraordinary emphasis on human free will; the cosmic struggle cannot be won without human participation; every human being must actively choose asha over druj in every moment</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Chinvat Bridge</strong> — at death, the soul crosses the Chinvat Bridge (Bridge of the Requiter); for the righteous, it is wide and easy to cross; for the wicked, it narrows to a razor\'s edge and they fall into the House of Lies (hell); on the fourth day after death, the soul reaches its destination</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Three-Day Journey</strong> — in the three days following death, the soul remains near the body; on the fourth day it is judged; the soul\'s urvan (moral self) is met by a beautiful maiden (the daena — personification of one\'s own conscience/religion) for the righteous or a hideous hag for the wicked</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Frashokereti (Renovation of the World)</strong> — the eschatological climax: at the end of time (after a cosmic period of 12,000 years), Ahura Mazda defeats Angra Mainyu; the dead are resurrected; a river of molten metal purifies all souls; the world is restored to its original perfect state; evil is permanently vanquished; the blessed enjoy eternal life in the renovated world</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Zoroastrianism\'s position on conversion is among the most restrictive of any religion. Traditionally, one must be born of a Zoroastrian father (and in some communities, both parents) to be Zoroastrian. This non-proselytizing stance has several explanations:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The religion was designed for a specific ethnic community (the ancient Iranians)</li>';
echo '<li>Centuries of persecution (after the Arab conquest of Persia in the 7th century CE) made caution about accepting outsiders a survival strategy</li>';
echo '<li>The Parsi community of India (Zoroastrian refugees from Persia who arrived in the 8th–10th centuries CE) is especially strict; Parsis do not accept converts and do not allow the children of Parsi women who marry non-Parsis to be initiated into the faith</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<p>This non-conversion policy has led to a severe demographic crisis: the global Zoroastrian population of approximately 110,000–200,000 is declining rapidly due to small family sizes, intermarriage, and no replacement through conversion. Some Iranian Zoroastrian communities (as opposed to Parsi) have been more willing to accept converts, and a growing "traditionalist reform" movement argues for accepting sincere converts to prevent extinction of the faith.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>In the Zoroastrian worldview, apostasy (abandoning the faith) is a profound spiritual failure — choosing druj over asha, the lie over the truth. Historically, under the Sassanid Persian Empire (224–651 CE) when Zoroastrianism was the state religion, apostasy could carry severe penalties. After the Arab conquest and the gradual conversion of Persia to Islam, Zoroastrians became a persecuted minority and apostasy to Islam was the primary concern — often driven by social and economic pressure rather than sincere conviction. Today, apostasy carries social consequences (exclusion from community events, loss of access to Zoroastrian institutions) but no legal consequences in countries where Zoroastrians live (India, Iran, USA, UK, Canada, Australia).</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Navjote (Parsi) / Sedreh-Pushi (Iranian)</strong> — the most important Zoroastrian rite of passage; the initiation ceremony in which a child (typically between 7 and 15) is formally invested with the sudreh (sacred white inner garment) and the kusti (sacred cord woven from wool); from this point the child is a full member of the faith and responsible for wearing the sudreh and kusti at all times</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Sudreh</strong> — the sacred undershirt; white, symbolizing purity; must be worn next to the skin at all times; represents the armor of righteousness</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Kusti</strong> — the sacred cord; worn around the waist over the sudreh; made of 72 threads of fine wool (representing the 72 chapters of the Yasna); tied and untied three times daily during the Kusti prayer (Nirang-i-Kusti), reaffirming commitment to Good Thoughts, Good Words, Good Deeds</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Birth itself</strong> — the newborn is shown fire and light; prayers are recited; the child is considered under Ahura Mazda\'s protection</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Ashirvad (Blessing)</strong> — the Zoroastrian marriage ceremony performed by a Dastur (priest); the couple are bound together with the kusti cord while the priest recites Avestan prayers; the ceremony involves fire as the sacred witness</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Endogamy</strong> — strong preference (and in Parsi community, often strict requirement) for marriage within the Zoroastrian community; a Parsi woman who marries a non-Parsi traditionally loses community membership and her children are not considered Zoroastrian</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Interfaith marriage</strong> — causes demographic anxiety in the already shrinking Zoroastrian community; a significant point of contention between traditionalists and reformers</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Death and Burial — The Tower of Silence</h3>';
echo '<p>Zoroastrian funerary practice is among the most distinctive in any religion, rooted in the theological commitment to keeping the four sacred elements (fire, water, earth, air) undefiled by death and decay:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>No cremation</strong> — fire is sacred to Ahura Mazda; burning a corpse defiles the sacred fire</li>';
echo '<li><strong>No burial</strong> — the earth is sacred; burying a corpse defiles the sacred earth and the water table</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Dakhma (Tower of Silence)</strong> — the traditional Zoroastrian solution: a circular stone tower on which the body is exposed to the sun and to vultures; the flesh is consumed by birds within hours; the bones, dried by the sun, are deposited in an ossuary pit at the center of the tower; this returns the body to nature without defiling any sacred element</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Decline of sky burial</strong> — vulture populations have collapsed across South Asia due to diclofenac (a veterinary drug) poisoning; the towers of silence in Mumbai (Malabar Hill) can no longer function as intended; solar concentrators (large mirrors to accelerate decomposition) have been installed as an alternative</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Diaspora</strong> — Zoroastrians in the West typically use conventional burial or cremation under religious dispensation, though some traditionalists refuse cremation on theological grounds</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Mourning</strong> — four days of prayer and ritual; the soul is believed to be near the body for three days before crossing the Chinvat Bridge on the fourth day; prayers are offered at 30 days, 1 year (hamaspathmaidyem), and annually thereafter</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Reincarnation and Karma</h3>';
echo '<p>Mainstream Zoroastrianism does <strong>not</strong> teach reincarnation. The soul lives one life, crosses the Chinvat Bridge at death, is judged, and goes to either the House of Song (paradise — Garo Demana) or the House of Lies (hell — Druj Demana) or, for those who balanced good and evil equally, a neutral intermediate realm (Hamestagan). At the Frashokereti (final renovation), all souls are purified through the river of molten metal and united in eternal blessed existence.</p>';
echo '<p>This single-life moral accounting — without reincarnation — places even more weight on each life\'s choices. There is no second chance in another incarnation; the choices made in this one life determine one\'s post-mortem fate. This makes Zoroastrian ethics peculiarly urgent.</p>';
echo '<p>The Zoroastrian karma equivalent is <strong>Asha vs Druj</strong> — the accumulation of righteous deeds (asha) and their opposites (druj) which are weighed at the Chinvat Bridge. The Gathas describe the soul\'s deeds, words, and thoughts being weighed; the result determines the soul\'s destination. This is not karma in the Hindu sense (which operates across multiple lives) but a single-life moral ledger reviewed at death.</p>';

